{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1778560760,"nonce":"6BqNWH3nl+pB+18stzf9VchPhh0=","message":"**Decoupling framing consultation — synthesis (2026-05-11)**\n\nExternal consultation with Gemini 3.1 Pro and GPT-5.5 via codex on whether the regulator-vs-tracker framing of this acid test is correct, whether the MVP (`410d7ac`) approach is valid, and what the best path forward is. Codex was given a second round to critique the synthesized path. Full prompts and responses at `results/d448c9d/consultations/2026-05-11_decoupling_framing/`.\n\n\nA few terms used below that aren't in the issue body:\n\n- **Velocity deflation for safety** (Gemini): hypothesis that the GRU intentionally slows its nominal trajectory under adversarial training to leave actuator headroom — produces Δv \u003c 0, not just Δv = 0.\n- **Objective mismatch** (Codex): hypothesis that the GRU and analytical Riccati optimize different cost functions (extra rlrmp losses, regularizers, catch trials, noise — none in Riccati setup) so their Δv signatures are not comparable.\n- **Adversary mismatch** (Codex): flavor-B's `ΔA·x` Frobenius-bounded adversary class is not equivalent to the analytical H∞ free additive disturbance with full-state `B_w`.\n- **Matched-objective ladder** (Codex): train every architecture (Riccati → trained LTV regulator → tracker → affine recurrent → GRU) under identical plant/cost/horizon/adversary/delay. Architectural Δv differences are only interpretable after this calibration.\n- **Pareto diagnostic** (Codex): x-axis nominal peak velocity, y-axis robustness metric. Decoupling = \"for equal/better robustness, the adversarial model does not need higher peak velocity.\"\n\n\nThe framing is fundamentally correct: Δv is the right behavioral signature for distinguishing regulator from decoupled tracker. The MVP's constant x_nom is the structural flaw. The fix is a true trajectory tracker (parameterized `x_nom(t)`), tested via a 3-phase plan: frozen-tracker proof of existence, learnable warm-started tracker, then GRU representational analysis via local linearization. Additionally proposes three explanations for the GRU's *negative* (not just neutral) Δv: velocity deflation for safety, observer-gain shift under adversarial training, bimodal attractor classes.\n\n\nThe framing is too narrow. Δv is one point on a Pareto diagnostic, not \"proof of decoupling.\" The GRU result should be interpreted as \"the GRU is not converging to the same H∞ optimum as the Riccati / linear-controller game\" — tracker decoupling is one candidate mechanism among objective mismatch, adversary mismatch, optimizer basin effects. The 30× discrepancy between trained LTV regulator (+78% from MVP) and analytical Riccati (+1-27% on the same regime) is a louder alarm than the tracker story and must be closed first. The matched-objective ladder is the missing experiment; direction-dependent `u_ff(t, target)` is essential for center-out.\n\n\nGemini accepts the regulator-vs-tracker framing and prescribes architecture engineering as the next step. Codex argues the framing itself may be premature — until plant, cost, horizon, adversary, and delay are matched across all controllers, no architectural comparison is interpretable. Both converge on largely the same experiments; they diverge on *ordering* and on what counts as conclusive.\n\n\nAfter receiving my initial synthesis (Tier 1 = GRU affine decomposition first), Codex pushed back hard: GRU affine decomposition is observational and local — it tells you whether the GRU *looks* tracker-like near its nominal trajectory, not whether tracker structure *caused* Δv decoupling. The nominal/feedback power split is ill-defined on the undisturbed trajectory (local feedback correction is zero by construction). `induced_gain.py` is useful machinery but not a complete GRU affine-decomposition tool — a new wrapper exposing `u_nominal`, `∂u/∂x_plant`, `∂u/∂h`, residual nonlinearity, and perturbation-response decompositions is needed. Most importantly: promote the Riccati round-trip to the *first decisive move*. If trained LTV regulator still gives +78% where Riccati gives +1-27% under matched objective, **stop doing architecture comparisons** — the training objective is the puzzle, not architecture.\n\nI accept this update. The ordering below reflects it.\n\n\n| Tier | What | Issue | Cost |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| 0 | Trajectory/cost audit across existing controllers (baseline GRU, flavor-B GRU, trained linear, Riccati) — surface unmatched axes before any new training | [`b6084c7`](git-bug://b6084c7) | hours, no training |\n| 1 | Matched-objective Riccati round-trip — make trained LTV regulator reproduce analytical Δv. Single highest-priority experiment | sub-item 2.2 of [`66a3374`](git-bug://66a3374) | new training, laptop-CPU scale |\n| 2 | GRU affine decomposition + bimodality clustering — demoted to \"useful diagnostic.\" Needs a new wrapper around `induced_gain.py`. Measure under standardized perturbations, not on undisturbed trajectory | [`0c95d6b`](git-bug://0c95d6b) | no training |\n| 3 | Fixed-direction matched-objective sweep with tracker variants (regulator + true LTV tracker + K-frozen tracker + u_ff-frozen tracker) | sub-item 2.1 of [`66a3374`](git-bug://66a3374) | new training, laptop-CPU |\n| 4 | GRU under matched objective — conclusive architecture test | [`0083c5f`](git-bug://0083c5f) | new training |\n\n\n- Direction-dependent `u_ff(t, target)` is essential for center-out reaching.\n- Nominal/feedback power split must be measured under standardized perturbations, not on undisturbed trajectories.\n- Delay treatment matters — a delayed GRU may solve a fundamentally different problem than full-state Riccati.\n- Bimodality of flavor-B means averages across replicates are misleading. Use replicate-level analysis throughout.\n- Empirical adversary rollouts vs analytical induced norms are not interchangeable. Pick one and stay with it.\n\nFull synthesis: `results/d448c9d/consultations/2026-05-11_decoupling_framing/synthesis.md`. Raw consultation responses in the same directory.","files":null}]}